^d@e@2So, if I responded 5@C, and ben bid 5@D he would be asking me for the Q of trumps. And, @E@3if I bid 5@D and ben bid 5@H, he would also be asking me about the Q of trumps. |
pg| ***** 27 ***** |


at|

Assume ben wants to do the Q ask. If he did, responder rebids the trump suit without the Q of trumps (5@S in this case.) So a 5@S bid by me over the Q ask denies the Q of spades. If I have the Q of spades, I bid a suit in which I have a K (5@H in this case.) If I have the Q of spades, but no outside Kings I bid 5NT. |
pg| ***** 28 ***** |


at|

The reason I said that you should only play Q ask if you play 1430 is because you are more likely to want to know about the Q of trump if responder has one A than zero aces. The 1430 keeps the bidding lower when responder has 1 ace. But, If you don’t play Q ask, there is no point in playing 1430, because you would rather keep the bidding lower with fewer aces (hence 0314.) Thus, in my opinion you should only play 1430 if you play the Q ask. |
